---
import { Code } from 'astro:components';
import GuideLayout from '../../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro';

const title = 'Interaction · Chartly';
---

<GuideLayout title={title}>
  <div class="prose-guide">
    <header class="mb-12 border-b border-border pb-8">
      <p class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-brand-strong">Interaction</p>
      <h1 class="mb-4 text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-text">Interaction</h1>
      <p class="max-w-[720px] text-lg leading-relaxed text-muted">
        Making charts respond to the mouse. Chartly ships two tooltip components
        &mdash; one for Cartesian, one for polar &mdash; plus the raw hover
        primitives for anything custom.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section id="tooltip" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-text">Tooltip</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">
        Drop <code>&lt;Tooltip&gt;</code> as the last child of
        <code>&lt;ChartContainer&gt;</code>. It renders an invisible overlay
        that captures mouse events, finds the nearest data point, and calls
        your render function with the point&rsquo;s pixel position and datum.
      </p>
      <Code lang="tsx" theme="github-dark" code={`<Tooltip<Row> indicatorStroke="#5eead4" dotFill="#5eead4">
  {({ x, y, datum }) => (
    <g transform={\`translate(\${x + 12}, \${y - 50})\`}>
      <rect width={140} height={44} rx={6} fill="#0f172a" stroke="#334155" />
      <text x={12} y={20} fontSize={11} fill="#94a3b8">{datum.month}</text>
      <text x={12} y={36} fontSize={13} fill="#5eead4">\${datum.revenue}</text>
    </g>
  )}
</Tooltip>`} />
      <p class="mt-6">
        Placing the tooltip <em>last</em> matters: SVG paints and hit-tests in
        document order, so the invisible rect ends up on top and catches every
        pointer event cleanly.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="polar-tooltip" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-text">PolarTooltip</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">
        The polar equivalent. Reads the currently-hovered slice or polygon from
        the polar context and passes it to your render function. HTML content
        via <code>&lt;foreignObject&gt;</code> works well for multi-line pie
        callouts.
      </p>
      <Code lang="tsx" theme="github-dark" code={`<PolarTooltip<Row>>
  {({ datum, cx, cy }) => (
    <foreignObject x={cx - 65} y={cy - 28} width={130} height={56}>
      <div className="tooltip-card">
        {datum.category} &mdash; \${datum.revenue}
      </div>
    </foreignObject>
  )}
</PolarTooltip>`} />
    </section>

    <section id="nearest-point" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-text">Nearest-point lookup</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">
        For linear and time scales, Chartly uses <code>d3-array</code>&rsquo;s
        <code>bisector</code> &mdash; an <code>O(log n)</code> binary search
        &mdash; to locate the nearest data point to the mouse. Even with 100,000
        points, lookup stays sub-microsecond.
      </p>
      <p class="mb-4">
        Band scales fall back to an <code>O(n)</code> pixel-distance loop
        because there is no meaningful pixel-to-category inverse. Category
        counts are usually small, so this is fine in practice.
      </p>
      <p>
        Mouse position is read via
        <code>event.clientX - rect.left</code> against the overlay&rsquo;s
        bounding rect &mdash; a cross-browser reliable pattern that avoids
        <code>offsetX</code> quirks on SVG in Firefox.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="custom-hover" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-text">Custom hover UI</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">
        For scenarios where <code>&lt;Tooltip&gt;</code> is too opinionated,
        you can build your own by combining a plain SVG rect with the chart
        context. This lets you build crosshairs, multi-series callouts, or
        highlight overlays.
      </p>
      <Code lang="tsx" theme="github-dark" code={`function Crosshair() {
  const { data, xScale, yScale, width, height, margin } = useChartContext();
  const [active, setActive] = useState<number | null>(null);

  return (
    <>
      {active !== null && (
        <line
          x1={xScale(data[active].month)}
          x2={xScale(data[active].month)}
          y1={margin.top}
          y2={height - margin.bottom}
          stroke="#5eead4"
          strokeDasharray="4 4"
        />
      )}
      <rect
        x={margin.left} y={margin.top}
        width={width - margin.left - margin.right}
        height={height - margin.top - margin.bottom}
        fill="transparent"
        onMouseMove={/* ... find nearest index ... */}
        onMouseLeave={() => setActive(null)}
      />
    </>
  );
}`} />
      <p class="mt-6">
        A public <code>useHoverState</code> hook is on the roadmap for
        consumers who want the nearest-point math without building the pointer
        overlay from scratch. Open an issue if you need it now.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="mt-16 flex items-center justify-between border-t border-border pt-8">
      <a href="/guide/axes/" class="text-sm text-muted hover:text-text">
        <span aria-hidden="true">&larr;</span> Axes &amp; grid
      </a>
      <a href="/guide/styling/" class="text-sm text-muted hover:text-text">
        Styling <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</GuideLayout>
